column32:
It seems like the user management "constructs" the username by using the network name and the given user name.

Logging in as admin will query the db for the user "test-network-admin".

The problem: In the hyperledger explorer config there are two places where the name can be set.

1) config.json: see networkname_1
{code:java}
{
	"network-configs": {
		"test-network1": {
			"name": "networkname_1",
			"profile": "./test.json",
			"enableAuthentication": true
		}
	},
	"license": "Apache-2.0"
}
{code}
2) in the test.json: networkname_2
{code:java}
{
	"name": "networkname_2",
	"version": "1.0.0",
	"license": "Apache-2.0",
	"client": {
		"tlsEnable": true,
...
{code}
There is no check that you enter the same name in both places!

The code that creates the admin account uses the name from config.json (networkname_1).

The login handler uses the name from test.json (networkname_2) and queries the psql db for networkname_2-admin...

Which obviously does not work.

Why is the network name used in the first place? The pqsl db has an entry network name.

