When Fabric-ca is configured for the organization in the connection profile, Explorer uses credential generated by fabric-ca for accessing to fabric network.

h3. Case: Enabled Fabric CA

You need to specify the following keys:
* client.caCredential
** id
** passowrd
* client.adminCredential
** affiliation
* organizations.[org name]
** certificateAuthorities
{code:json}
	"client": {
		"tlsEnable": true,
		"caCredential": {
			"id": "admin",
			"password": "adminpw"
		},
		"adminCredential": {
			"id": "exploreradmin",
			"password": "exploreradminpw",
			"affiliation": "org1.department1"
		},
		"enableAuthentication": true,

	...

	"organizations": {
		"org1": {
			"mspid": "Org1ExampleCom",
			"peers": ["peer0-org1"],
			"certificateAuthorities": ["ca0"]
		}
	},

{code}

h3. Case: Disabled Fabric CA

You need to specify the following keys:
* organizations.[org name]
** adminPrivateKey
** signedCert
{code:json}
	"client": {
		"tlsEnable": true,
		"adminCredential": {
			"id": "exploreradmin",
			"password": "exploreradminpw",
		},
		"enableAuthentication": true,

	...

	"organizations": {
		"org1": {
			"mspid": "Org1ExampleCom",
			"adminPrivateKey": {
				"path": "[path to private key]"
			},
			"peers": ["peer0-org1"],
			"signedCert": {
				"path": "[path to cert]"
			}
		}
	},

{code}

