column32:
The client websocket URL now supports \{host}

{port}

structure, but it is limited to one Explorer deployment per URL (e.g. _[https://explorer1.example.com/|https://explorer1.example.com/_] or [https://explorer2.example.com/|https://explorer2.example.com/_], but not [https://www.example.com/ws/explorer1/|https://www.example.com/ws/explorer1/_]_ and [_https://www.example.com/ws/explorer2/_|https://www.example.com/ws/explorer2/_]), because it is located at root.

When combining different Hyperledger deployments where a proxy is redirecting calls to them, it is not possible to run one Explorer per deployment. The proxy can't handle a call to a specific Explorer.

Allowing a path redirection (e.g.: /ws/explorer1/) would help to better manage different deployments.

Currently a hack could be done by managing headers for websockets in the proxy, but it should not be a permanent solution.

