> psql postgres -v dbname=$DATABASE -v user=$USR -v passwd=$PASSWD -f ./updatepg.sql ;;
> linux*) psql -v dbname=$DATABASE -v user=$USR -v passwd=$PASSWD -f ./explorerpg.sql ;
> psql -v dbname=$DATABASE -v user=$USR -v passwd=$PASSWD -f ./updatepg.sql ;;
> esac
psql: FATAL: role "user" does not exist
psql: FATAL: role "user" does not exist

"user" is actual name of user on my ubuntu. Solution is to run script with user that exists in postgres database as a default which is postgres.

So change in the code would look like this:



Instead of:



linux*) psql -v dbname=$DATABASE -v user=$USER -v passwd=$PASSWD -f ./explorerpg.sql ;
psql -v dbname=$DATABASE -v user=$USER -v passwd=$PASSWD -f ./updatepg.sql ;;
esac

Use this:

linux*) *sudo -u postgres* psql -v dbname=$DATABASE -v user=$USER -v passwd=$PASSWD -f ./explorerpg.sql ;
*sudo -u postgres* psql -v dbname=$DATABASE -v user=$USER -v passwd=$PASSWD -f ./updatepg.sql ;;
esac

Or shell has to be running with the postgress user.

